1 Introduction

Patient length-of-stay (LOS) is defined as the duration of time a patient stays admitted in a hospital. With massive volumes of existing patient information, machine learning is used to predict LOS for better patient service outcomes and optimal resource allocations. This is a classification problem because our response variable - length of stay is divided into 11 different classes, ranging from 0-10 days to more than 100 days. Due to time constraints and a high class imbalance with the majority of independent features being categorical variables, in the current study, we focused on predicting whether the patient stays at the hospital < 30 days or > 30 days. In return, an accurate prediction of the patient LOS will provide hospitals to better allocate resources to meet the unexpected long stays, in this case, patients staying more than 30 days.

2 Data Description

Healthcare Analytics II dataset was generated based on the hospital records. The data contains 318,438 records of patients, and consists of 17 different categorical or numerical features regarding the environmental, social and personal information of each patient, plus the target variable, Stay. Stay variable is divided into 10 different levels (0 to 100+ days). Some patients had multiple entries because they might have been infected by multiple diseases or involved in an incidence at different times, thus the cases were considered independently.

4 Feature Engineering

Initially, the target variable length of stay was transformed from multi-class to binary class (>30 days or <30 days of hospital admission) due to a high class imbalance issue, and such transformation solved the issue of class imbalance (shown in Figure. 3). To address the categorical variables for the linear-based machine learning algorithms such as linear discriminant analysis (LDA) and logistic regression, categorical variables were replaced with dummy variables. Lastly, the ordinal variable, age, was converted to a numerical variable by the order (from 1 representing the lowest age group to 10 representing the highest age group) instead of assigning each category to a dummy variable to prevent losing the constraint of the order.

5.1 Logistic regression

5.1.1 Methodology

A logistic regression model is useful for binary classification issues, thus, logistic regression is selected to be one of the algorithms for patients LOS. Logistic regression is based on a linear function. It uses log transformation that allows logistic regression to mapping the function to output a bounded estimated probability between 0 and 1. The probability estimate of logistic regression as an output can be used to estimate the confidence of the predicted value to be an actual value, when given a new input. In the current study, 0.5 was set to be the linear decision boundary. Thus, if the hypothesis is greater than 0.5, the prediction belongs to the 1 class; if the hypothesis function is less than 0.5, the prediction belongs to the 0 class.

5.1.2 Feature selection

In order to find the best model, a forward stepwise feature selection was utilised. The forward selection begins with a null model and iteratively adds new features to it in order to improve the model performance. The selection process will stop when the added feature no longer improves the model performance. The model performance is evaluated through Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), AIC estimates the information lost by a given model and a lower AIC value indicates better model performance.

# Run algorithms using 10-fold cross validation
control <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)

# Feature selection process and print out important features for the model

5.2 XGBoost

5.2.1 Methodology

Boosting algorithms seek to improve the prediction accuracy by training a series of base models iteratively, and in each iteration, the model will compensate for the weaknesses of its predecessors. (Zhang, 2019). Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) is an optimised distributed gradient boosting which attempts to minimise the loss of a model while iterating the base model and using a gradient-descent like procedure. (Brownlee, 2020). Since we are dealing with a binary classification model in this report, the base model in our boosting algorithm will be a gradient boosted tree. More specifically, the tree is grown sequentially to minimise the misclassification from the previous tree.

# preparing matrix for XGBoost
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data =  as.matrix(train_dummy), label = as.numeric(stay.train_dummy)-1)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_dummy), label = as.numeric(stay.test_dummy)-1)
labels <- as.numeric(stay.train_dummy)-1
ts_label <- as.numeric(stay.test_dummy)-1


### Default Model
#default parameters
params <- list(booster = "gbtree", objective = "binary:logistic", eta=0.01, gamma=0, max_depth=5, min_child_weight=1, subsample=1, colsample_bytree=1)

#first default - model training
xgb1 <- xgb.train (params = params, data = dtrain, nrounds = 66, watchlist = list(val=dtest,train=dtrain), print_every_n = 10, early_stopping_rounds = 10, maximize = F , eval_metric = "error")

5.2.2 Hyperparameter Tuning

gbtree booster is selected as our base model to solve a classification problem, and a hyperparameter tuning process was taken in order to maximise the performance of our XGBoost.

  • eta is one of the most important parameters. It controls the learning rate, where lower eta leads to slower computation yet more careful search of the maxima. To set a smaller eta, the nrounds parameter needs to be set higher to avoid termination of search before reaching the maximum point. (tune range: 0.01 - 0.3)

  • max_depth parameter controls the depth of a tree. Depth of the tree determines the complexity of the model, and a deeper model is more likely to be overfitting potentially. Therefore, optimisation of the max depth parameter is crucial to avoid overfitting issues. (tune range: 3 - 10)

  • Min_child_weight is the minimum number of instances needed in a child node. Having the child weight stops the tree from splitting infinitely, and in return, controls overfitting. (tune range: 1 - 5)

  • Subsample and colsample_bytree are controlling the number of samples of features supplied to a tree, which again prevent overfitting. (tune range: 0.5 - 1)

Learner is created from the MLR package, which will be used in the tuneParams function. Random search is applied to search for 20 different parameter combinations randomly from the specified tuning range and tested on the training set using 5 fold cross validation. The best parameter set is defined as the one that returns the highest accuracy. Eta is not included in the random search process, but rather is tuned manually within the range 0.01 - 0.3.

if (longrun){

#create learner
lrn <- makeLearner("classif.xgboost",predict.type = "response")
lrn$par.vals <- list(objective="binary:logistic", eval_metric="error", nrounds=70L, eta=0.05)

#set parameter space
params <- makeParamSet(makeDiscreteParam("booster",values = c("gbtree")), makeIntegerParam("max_depth",lower = 3L,upper = 10L), makeNumericParam("min_child_weight",lower = 1L, upper = 5L), makeNumericParam("subsample",lower = 0.5,upper = 1), makeNumericParam("colsample_bytree",lower = 0.5,upper = 1))

#set resampling strategy
rdesc <- makeResampleDesc("CV", stratify = T,iters=5L)

# Random search handler
# search strategy
ctrl <- makeTuneControlRandom(maxit = 20L) # randomly search for 10 different sets of parameters 


#create tasks
train_dummy_full = train_dummy
test_dummy_full = test_dummy

train_dummy_full['Stay'] = stay.train_dummy
test_dummy_full['Stay'] = stay.test_dummy

traintask <- makeClassifTask(data = train_dummy_full,target = "Stay")
testtask <- makeClassifTask(data = test_dummy_full,target = "Stay")

# parameter tuning
mytune <- tuneParams(learner = lrn, task = traintask, resampling = rdesc, measures = acc, par.set = params, control = ctrl, show.info = T)


# Hyperparameter tuning results

5.3 Random Forest

5.3.1 Methodology

Random Forest is chosen to be our third classification model to predict the patient stay in the hospital. Random Forest is a supervised machine learning algorithm that combines multiple decision trees into one single result (Sklearn.ensemble.randomforestclassifier. (n.d.)). It generates a random subset of the features and grow an uncorrelated forest, in other words, it produces aggregated predictions to result in more precise and robust outcomes .Another benefit random forest provides is that it tends not to overfit and ability to handle non-linear numeric and categorical predictors.

5.3.2 Hyperparameter Tuning

Ranger package is adopted to train random forest in our study, as Ranger package is faster in terms of run-time compared to the traditional random forest package. Parameter search is crafted for the two key hyperparameters in ranger, which are num.treees and mtry. num.trees refers to the number of trees to be built in the model and mtry refers to the number of variables to be included in the first split. We test num.trees from 300 to 800 and set 100 as an interval while num.trees is set to run from 3 to 15, using 3 as an interval. Then, these models were run one by one and compared the accuracy to find the optimal hyperparameter. Based on the plots and table of all 30 combinations (six different ntree*five different mtry), the highest accuracy (79.59%) was achieved within the training set when mtry is 3 and num.trees is 800.

# hyperparameter tuning
hyper_grid <- expand.grid(
  mtry       = seq(3,15, by = 3),
  num.trees = seq(300,800, by =100),
  accuracy   = 0
)


for(i in 1:nrow(hyper_grid)) {
    # train modelz
    rf <- ranger(
      formula        = Stay ~ .,
      data           = datatrain,
      num.trees      = hyper_grid$num.trees[i],
      mtry           = hyper_grid$mtry[i],
      importance = 'impurity')
    # add accuracy to grid
    hyper_grid$accuracy[i] <- confusionMatrix(rf$confusion.matrix)$overall['Accuracy']
}

nrow(hyper_grid)
position = which.max(hyper_grid$accuracy)
head(hyper_grid[order(hyper_grid$accuracy,decreasing = TRUE),],5)
tuning <- ggplot(hyper_grid, aes(x = num.trees, y = accuracy, color = mtry)) +
  geom_point() + theme_bw() + labs(x='num.trees', y="Accuracy")
tuning +scale_color_gradient(low="red", high="blue")

5.4 Linear Discriminant Analysis

5.4.1 Methodology

Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a supervised machine learning technique that models the difference between the classes, aiming to find a linear combination of features that separates two or more classes of events. The established features then can be used as a linear classifier.(Yang, 2020)

LDA is similar to logistic regression, whereas both algorithms explain the target variable by the values of independent predictor variables. However, LDA has a stricter assumption that predictor variables should be normally distributed. In addition, LDA has a closed-form solution (scikit-learn), which means the training and inference time for the model is negligible with a large dataset. However, the downside of the LDA closed-form solution is that the initial parameters of the model only have a little impact on the results, which makes it difficult to improve the model performance.

5.4.2 Feature Selection

Just like logistic regression, we used a forward feature selection algorithm on the LDA model to search for the best feature combinations, with a 5-fold cross-validation and 1% improvement in accuracy as the stopping criterion. Based on the forward feature selection, two features were enough to achieve the plateau of accuracy, and adding more features would provide less than 1% increase in accuracy. The final model for LDA consists of the features, Ward_TypeQ and visitors.with.patient.

stepclass(Stay ~ .,data = datatrain_dummy, method = 'lda', direction = 'forward',fold = 5,improvement = 0.01)
## correctness rate: 0.69218;  in: "visitors.with.patient";  variables (1): visitors.with.patient 
## correctness rate: 0.77258;  in: "Ward_TypeQ";  variables (2): visitors.with.patient, Ward_TypeQ 
## 
##  hr.elapsed min.elapsed sec.elapsed 
##       0.000      12.000       3.912
## method      : lda 
## final model : Stay ~ Ward_TypeQ + visitors.with.patient
## <environment: 0x657bd4f98>
## 
## correctness rate = 0.7726
# Find the probability cut-off when it maximises the combination of specificity and sensitivity
if (longrun){
threshold = seq(0.1,0.9,0.05)
lda.acclist = c()
lda.reclist = c()
lda.prelist = c()
folds <- createFolds(datatrain_dummy$Stay, k=10)
for (t in threshold){
  lda.models <- lapply(folds, function(f) MASS::lda(Stay ~ Ward_TypeQ + visitors.with.patient, data=datatrain_dummy[-f,]))
  lda.preds.cv <- mapply(function(model, f) predict(model,newdata = datatrain_dummy[f,-119])$posterior[,"0"], model = lda.models, f =   folds)
  lda.decision <- lapply(lda.preds.cv, function(f) as.factor(ifelse(f > t, 0, 1)))
  obs <- lapply(folds, function(x) datatrain_dummy$Stay[x])
  lda.metrics <- mapply(function(pred, obs) confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = obs),
                        pred = lda.decision, obs = obs,
                        SIMPLIFY = FALSE)
  lda.TP <- vapply(lda.metrics, function(cm) cm[["table"]][1, 1], numeric(1))
  lda.FP <- vapply(lda.metrics, function(cm) cm[["table"]][1, 2], numeric(1))
  lda.TN <- vapply(lda.metrics, function(cm) cm[["table"]][2, 2], numeric(1))
  lda.FN <- vapply(lda.metrics, function(cm) cm[["table"]][2, 1], numeric(1))
  lda.accuracy <- vapply(lda.metrics, function(cm) cm[["overall"]]["Accuracy"], numeric(1))
  lda.precision = lda.TP/(lda.TP+lda.FP)
  lda.recall = lda.TP/(lda.TP+lda.FN)
  lda.acclist = c(lda.acclist, sum(lda.accuracy)/10)
  lda.reclist = c(lda.reclist, sum(lda.recall)/10)
  lda.prelist = c(lda.prelist, sum(lda.precision)/10)
}
plot(threshold, lda.acclist, type = "b", ylab = "10 fold result",xaxt = "n", ylim = c(0,1))
axis(side = 1, at = seq(0,1,0.05), labels = seq(0,1,0.05))
lines(threshold, lda.reclist,col = 'red',type = "b")
lines(threshold, lda.prelist,col = 'blue',type = "b")
legend(0.1, 0.3, legend=c("accuracy", "recall","precision"), fill = c("black","blue","red"))
}

5.4.3 Final Model And Result

The final LDA model is trained using the entire training set and tested in the test data. The final LDA model has the accuracy of 77.43%, F1-score of 83.36% and the sensitivity close to 95%. However, the specificity for the LDA model is only 51.81%. Overall, the performance of LDA is comparable to the other models of the current study despite the low number of features used for prediction.

6 Performance Evaluation and Discussion

The current study aimed to establish the best model to accurately predict the new patients, who will stay in the hospital for longer than 30 days through a comparison of the performance of each model. The classification report and ROC-AUC are utilised to estimate the performance of our four models.

roc.list <- list(roc.xgboost,roc.rf,roc.lda,roc.glm)
ggroc(roc.list,legacy.axes = TRUE)+geom_abline() +
  ggtitle("ROC curves") +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = c("XGBoost",
                                  "Random Forest",
                                  "LDA",
                                  "logistic regression"))

Figure 7. ROC curves for four models

Measurement Logistic Regression XGBoost Random Forest Linear Discriminant Analysis
AUC 0.8267 0.8322 0.7553 0.8033

Table 2. AUC for each model

Receiver operating characteristic curve (ROC curve) and Area under the ROC Curve (AUC value) were used to measure the ability of each model to predict unlabelled data accurately, and a higher AUC value indicates a better performance of the model. According to the ROC curve and AUC value, the ensemble learning models (XGBoost and random forest) are better compared to the linear models (LDA, Logistic Regression), and random forest has the highest AUC value (0.8322).

Measurement Logistic Regression XGBoost Random Forest Linear Discriminant Analysis
Accuracy 77.78% 79.75% 79.72% 77.43%
Sensitivity 76.54% 95.05% 94.43% 94.88%
Specificity 80.71% 57.29% 58.12% 51.81%
F1 Score 82.87% 84.81% 84.71% 83.34%

Table 3. Performance metrics for each model

Table 3. shows the comparative classification results across different models with different machine learning algorithms. The XGBoost model produced the highest accuracy (79.75%) for predicting the duration of hospital admission of a patient, while the LDA model produced the lowest accuracy among all the models (77.43%). Despite the low variation in accuracy across different models, the sensitivity and specificity results varied significantly. The logistic regression model was able to make accurate predictions for the patients LOS (> 30 days and < 30 days) proportionally (Sensitivity: 76.54%, Specificity: 80.71%), whereas the other models had significantly lower specificity (below 60%) in comparison to the logistic regression model. Achieving a high specificity is of great importance as specificity indicates the ability to predict the patients with > 30 days LOS, which, in turn, allows hospitals to better allocate resources appropriately to meet the unexpected long stay. In this regard, the logistic regression is chosen for the final model due to its ability to accurately identify the patients with longer than 30 days of hospital admission.

The computation time is also an important aspect to consider to determine reasonable run-time to solve a task. Ensemble learning models had a slower run-time compared to the linear-based models. The random forest model had the slowest run time due to a high number of estimators, and the XGBoost was the second slowest. In contrast, Logistic regression has the quickest run-time indicating the highest timewise efficiency as well as the best performance to accurately distinguish the patients, who will stay longer than 30 days in the hospital. The LDA was slightly slower to run than logistic regression because the time complexity of lda is O(nd2) but the time complexity of logistic regression is O(nd).

6.1 Limitation

Due to the computational limitation and huge data size, some methods couldnt be implemented, for example grid search and SVM(support vector machine). Random search is used in the XGBoost method, it is ideal if XGBoost could implement grid search in the future which will potentially find better hyperparameter combinations. In addition to computational limitations, another limitation is unbalanced dataset. After merging the target class Stay from multi-class to binary-class, it is still not perfectly balanced. The imbalance problem could potentially leads to poor specificity scores in Random Forest, LDA and XGBoost.

6.2 Future Work

In the future, we could implement our model on more powerful machines to enable more efficient calculation. We are also planning to implement more advanced classifiers such as neural networks. This is a much powerful model with numbers of hidden layers to improve calculation which could potentially improve the specificity. For the unbalanced problem, oversampling and downsampling techniques can be employed to obtain more robust results and might achieve high prediction performance. Finally, after using more advanced methods and solving the imbalance problem, we could leave the multi-class variable Stay unchanged in the future and do a multi-class classification to give a more precise prediction on days of stay.

7 Conclusion

In summary, we were able to accurately predict 75% of the LOS of the new patients. However, as the significance of this study is to allow hospitals to better allocate the resources for the patients with unexpectedly long LOS in particular, we placed emphasis on the specificity to estimate the model performance. Thus, the logistic regression model was chosen as our final model, as aforementioned, due to its ability to accurately predict the negative label.
